Lab One: CNN Visualization¶

Xingming Qu, Bowei Tian

1. Based on the blog post above, create and argue for one reason you might use DeepDream to analyze a CNN visually. Write out this argument in text for the lab using your own words. Alternatively, you can also argue for a counter argument (that is, why this is only artistic, not useful).¶

First I agree that DeepDream is useful to analyze a CNN visually.
In DeepDream, an arbitrary image or photo will be analyze by the network. As showed in the blog, one can easily visualize intermediate activations by pick a layer and ask the network to enhance whatever it detected(ask the network which part of the image was actived).
For exmaple, in the blog they used a blue sky picture as the input of the network. Becuase the network was trained mostly on images of animals, it then identified some parts of cloud and sky which resemble animals and made it more like animals. This shows the network really learned how to identified animals: Different filters learn to identify different features.
Therefore, the way of DeepDream detects objects and makes them more obvious can be regard as a way to visualize intermediate activations.

2. In groups, you should select a convolutional neural network model that has been pre-trained on a large dataset (preferably, ImageNet). These already trained models are readily available online through many mechanisms, including the keras.application package (Inception, Xception, VGG etc.). Explain the model you chose and why.¶

In this lab, Xception will be used. Because Xception is the start-of-art model in Keras and I have never used this network. Besides, the model is only 88MB, which is smaller than VGG and Inceptionv3.

There were some DeepDream implemented by Keras. Reference:https://github.com/notabee/Deep_dream/blob/master/deep_dream_keras.ipynb (Inceptionv3)
https://github.com/isarth/DeepDream/blob/master/deep%20dream2.ipynb (VGG16)
https://github.com/google/deepdream/blob/master/dream.ipynb (Caffe inceptionv3 )

In [4]:
# some useful function
# preprocess function. This function load a image and convert it to array
# add a batch dimension, and do the preprocessing
def preprocess_image(image_path):
    img = image.load_img(image_path) #loading image
    img = image.img_to_array(img) #convert to array
    img = np.expand_dims(img, axis=0) # add batch dimensions
    img = xception.preprocess_input(img) # preprocessing
    return img

# for interation. we only need read the img once and then we just preprocess arr
def preprocess_arr(img):
    img = np.expand_dims(img, axis=0) # add batch dimensions
    img = xception.preprocess_input(img) # preprocessing
    return img
 
# deprocess function. This function is used to convert a tensor into a valid image    
def deprocess_image(x):
    x = x.reshape((x.shape[1], x.shape[2], 3)) #reshaping to ( h,w,c )
    
    #deprocess
    x /= 2. 
    x += 0.5
    x *= 255.
    
    #clipping value out if range ( 0,255 ) ie out RGB value range
    x = np.clip(x, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
    return x

# resize a image. This function is used for 
def resize_img(img, size):
    img = np.copy(img)
    #ratios to multiply to image dimensions to resize
    factors = (1,
             float(size[0]/img.shape[1]),
             float(size[1]/img.shape[2]),
             1                
            )
    #applying ratios using scipy
    return  scipy.ndimage.zoom(img, factors, order=1)

# Random shift function
# percent is how much you want shift
# eg percent= 0.1 means the img will be ramdom shift in x and y with 0-10%
def shift_img(img, percent):
    img = np.copy(img)
    #ratios to multiply to image dimensions to shift
    factors = (1,
             random.uniform(-percent, percent),
            random.uniform(-percent, percent),
             1                
            )
    #applying ratios using scipy
    return  scipy.ndimage.shift(img, factors, order=1)

# this function is used for saving img at various steps 
def save_img(img, fname):
    pil_img = deprocess_image(np.copy(img))
    scipy.misc.imsave(fname, pil_img)

In [6]:
#initial total weighted loss of the activations of the selected layers 
def loss_init():
    loss = 0
    layer_dict = dict([layer.name, layer]for layer in model.layers) # making dictionary of layers and their instances
    
    for layer_name in  layer_contributions: # get coefficients and layer output    
        coeff = layer_contributions[layer_name]  # get coefficients of the given layer

        activations = layer_dict[layer_name].output # get layer instance activations
        print('Layer:',layer_name,'    output shape:',activations.shape)
        
        #normalizing and clipping borders
        # When sum all the output from different layers,the loss will become very large
        # So we we need to normalize it     
        scale = K.prod(K.cast(K.shape(activations), 'float32')) 
        
        # K.shape: Returns the symbolic shape of a tensor or variable.
        # K.cast: Casts a tensor to a different dtype and returns it.
        # K.prod: Multiplies the values in a tensor, alongside the specified axis.
        # eg: d=np.array([[1,1,1],[2,3,4]])
        # prod(d)= 1*1*1*2*3*4=24
    
        # clipping borders
        # not including first two pixel border of the width and height
        # avoid border artifacts by only involving nonborder pixels in the loss.
        loss += coeff * K.sum(K.square(activations[: ,2:-2, 2:-2, :]))/scale # summation and normaliziation 
     
    return loss

3.1 Using L1 gradient normalization for gradient updates¶

In [8]:
# We take the gradient of this loss using keras backend.gradients
gradients = K.gradients(loss, dream)[0] # gradient of loss wrt to dream image

########   Using L1 gradient normalization for gradient updates    #######
# the shape of gradients should be (1,x,y,3)
# Before performing gradient ascent, we divide the gradient tensor by its L1 norm 
# if this is the right way to caculate tensor's L1 norm:
# (the maximal number of the mean of the absolute values in the tensor). 
# We add a small epsilon term to the L1 norm to avoid division by zero.
gradients /= np.max(K.mean(K.abs(gradients)))+1e-7 # normalizing gradients
# another way
# grads /= K.maximum(K.mean(K.abs(grads)), 1e-7)

########   Using L1 gradient normalization for gradient updates    #######

output = [loss, gradients] # making list of loss and grads
loss_and_grads = K.function([dream], output) #keras functions for input and output
In [9]:
#getting loss and gradients wrt dream image
def fetch_loss_and_grad(img):
    outputs = loss_and_grads([img])
    return outputs[0], outputs[1]
  
#applying gradients on dream image via gradient ascent  
# iter is run gradient ascent for xxx steps
def gradient_ascent(img, iter, step_alpha):
    for i in range(iter):
        loss, grads = fetch_loss_and_grad(img) #loading loss and grading with current state of dream image
        img += step_alpha * grads #adding gradients to dream image by multiplying with step_alpha similarly to gradient descent's alpha

    return img

3.2 Adding random shifts/resizing in the process (as described in DeepDream)¶

In [10]:
def dream_maker( inputimg , step=0.01, octave = 3, octave_scale = 1.4, iter_times=20, addingshift=False):
    print('gradient_ascent_times:',iter_times)
      
    img = inputimg # inputimg should go through preprocessing
    
    original_shape = img.shape[1:3] #extracting ( h,w )
    #list of tuples---used for save different shapes
    succesive_shapes = [original_shape]
    
    #####    adding resizing in the process   #############
    for i in range(1,octave): #making reduced tuple of ( h,w )
        tuple_of_shapes = tuple([ int( shape/ (octave_scale ** i)) for shape in original_shape ]) 
        succesive_shapes.append( tuple_of_shapes )
    succesive_shapes = succesive_shapes[::-1] #reversing small to large
    
    original_img = np.copy(img) #copy image
    
    #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############
    smallest_original_image = resize_img( original_img, succesive_shapes[0] ) #resizing original image to smallest octave
    if addingshift==True:
        smallest_original_image = shift_img(smallest_original_image,0.1)
    #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############
    for shape in succesive_shapes:
      
        print('Processing image shape', shape)
        #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############
        img  = resize_img( img  , shape) #resizing image to shape 
        if addingshift==True:
            img  = shift_img( img  , 0.1)
        #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############

        # run gradient ascent for xxx steps, and learning late is 0.01
        img = gradient_ascent( img, iter_times, 0.01) #applying gradient ascent on current current size of the image

        upscaled_smallest_original = resize_img( smallest_original_image, shape ) #getting original image of the current size
        downsized_original_image = resize_img( original_img, shape ) # reducing size of high resolution to current size

        details = downsized_original_image - upscaled_smallest_original # details we get after subtracting and these will be added to pixelated image

        img += details # adding lost details due to resizing
      
         
    return deprocess_image(img)

4.1 Explain any clues that the iterative process gives for how the CNN discerns different classes, if any.¶

What we think is going on is that the raw images comes in for the first time and the neural network gives some high level abstraction and then goes into a feedback loop where it simply sees the higher level abstraction and adds more of it so that after 8 interations, you only see the high level abstractions and you loose the notion of the sky image.

# Let's try introduce new noise in the DeepDream process 
def dream_maker_with_noise( inputimg , step=0.01, octave = 3, octave_scale = 1.4, iter_times=20):
    print('gradient_ascent_times:',iter_times)
      
    img = inputimg # inputimg should go through preprocessing
    
    original_shape = img.shape[1:3] #extracting ( h,w )
    #list of tuples---used for save different shapes
    succesive_shapes = [original_shape]
    
    #####    adding resizing in the process   #############
    for i in range(1,octave): #making reduced tuple of ( h,w )
        tuple_of_shapes = tuple([ int( shape/ (octave_scale ** i)) for shape in original_shape ]) 
        succesive_shapes.append( tuple_of_shapes )
    succesive_shapes = succesive_shapes[::-1] #reversing small to large
    
    original_img = np.copy(img) #copy image
    
    #####    Adding random noise/resizing in the process   #############
    smallest_original_image = resize_img( original_img, succesive_shapes[0] ) #resizing original image to smallest octave

    smallest_original_image=random_noise(smallest_original_image, mode='salt',amount =0.03) #adding salt noise
    #####    Adding random noise/resizing in the process   #############
    for shape in succesive_shapes:
      
        print('Processing image shape', shape)
        #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############
        img  = resize_img( img  , shape) #resizing image to shape 

        img=random_noise(img, mode='salt',amount =0.03) #adding salt noise
        #####    Adding random shifts/resizing in the process   #############

        # run gradient ascent for xxx steps, and learning late is 0.01
        img = gradient_ascent( img, iter_times, 0.01) #applying gradient ascent on current current size of the image

        upscaled_smallest_original = resize_img( smallest_original_image, shape ) #getting original image of the current size
        #####    Adding random noise/resizing in the process   #############
        upscaled_smallest_original=random_noise(upscaled_smallest_original, mode='salt',amount =0.03) #adding salt noise
        downsized_original_image = resize_img( original_img, shape ) # reducing size of high resolution to current size
        #####    Adding random noise/resizing in the process   #############
        downsized_original_image=random_noise(downsized_original_image, mode='salt',amount =0.03)
        details = downsized_original_image - upscaled_smallest_original # details we get after subtracting and these will be added to pixelated image

        img += details # adding lost details due to resizing
      
         
    return deprocess_image(img)
